@@eThe Eastern Desert -- As Kowloon Sees It@@N

@@lHarbor Syndics' Distant Trade Intelligence Brief@@N

The eastern desert is not on our doorstep. No caravan from Kowloon
walks those dunes directly. But @@ysea lanes@@N connect what land
separates, and goods from desert oases reach our @@lTide Gate@@N through
Mafdet's coastal trade. What happens to the eastern corridor's water
affects salt ceramic prices in Coppersalt Bay within two seasons.

The @@yKeepers of Measure@@N governed by calibration: road stones set to
star angles, cistern basins graded by seasonal drift, caravan levies
assessed in @@Wwater rights@@N rather than coin. The Jade Magistracy reads
this with professional recognition. Assessment in material need rather
than abstract currency -- this is @@your language@@N.

@@yMeasure Script@@N -- where a single symbol encodes direction, time,
water volume, and legal status -- fascinates the Courier Lantern
Office. Our own @@ecolor-code system@@N compresses civic meaning into
visual shorthand. @@rCrimson@@N for emergency, @@gjade@@N for permits,
@@lblue@@N for harbor jurisdiction. Different medium, same impulse:
make law readable at a glance under crisis conditions.

The @@dIseth Reach@@N dried. This single fact reorganized an entire
civilization. Water courts became war tribunals. The @@rCharter Wars@@N
erupted. The Jade Magistracy circulates this as a @@rcautionary
document@@N. Kowloon sits on the Jhen River. We have water. But the
Ashfall Monsoon proved that @@yclean water@@N is never guaranteed.

The @@rJackal Synod@@N -- militarized funerary priesthoods who seized
shrine-cistern nodes and weaponized ritual access to water -- is an
abomination by Temple Circle standards. Funerary rites honor the
dead, not leverage the living. The Synod's three rival schools are
filed under @@rthreat doctrine@@N: Anointers hoarding old authority,
Keepers of Dry Mercy rationing suffering, and the @@rEclipsed Tongues@@N
seeking total depopulation.

The @@dLast Sand Regent@@N still issues decrees to a dead bureaucracy.
The Courier Lantern Office finds this most disturbing -- a policy
engine running without constituents. In Kowloon we call this a
@@rsealed record@@N: authority operating after accountability is gone.
The @@rBlack Ledger@@N rumor in our own cisterns carries the same fear:
@@dwhat governs when no one is watching?@@N

The desert teaches what Kowloon already knows. @@yWater is law.@@N
When water fails, law fails. When law fails, the dead go unnamed.
